I don't know what's going on on my end.

00:42:21.960 --> 00:42:25.559
I was just saying thank you so much
for sharing your experiences,

00:42:25.560 --> 00:42:28.679
but for putting such
a positive slant onto it.

00:42:28.680 --> 00:42:32.279
It's just there's so many
positive messages there.

00:42:32.280 --> 00:42:33.319
It was wonderful.

00:42:33.320 --> 00:42:34.519
Thank you. Thank you.

00:42:34.520 --> 00:42:37.413
Now, we have quite a few questions.

00:42:38.280 --> 00:42:41.639
The first one is, have you had instances

00:42:41.640 --> 00:42:46.719
where some of the teams have relied
on external accessibility vendors

00:42:46.720 --> 00:42:50.560
and not created their own
content or experiences?

00:42:54.162 --> 00:42:57.520
<v Lorna> Ooh, Lorenzo, I can't think of any.

00:42:59.360 --> 00:43:03.559
We definitely have elements

00:43:03.560 --> 00:43:07.799
at Sage that have done
their own accessibility

00:43:07.800 --> 00:43:14.120
thing and we've become aware
of that sometimes through the grapevine,

00:43:15.360 --> 00:43:21.059
but we haven't had anyone that--

00:43:21.060 --> 00:43:23.374
oh, maybe tells us, Lorenzo?

00:43:23.920 --> 00:43:26.359
Maybe they did their own thing?

00:43:26.360 --> 00:43:30.479
Lorenzo: Yes, but they focused on it,
which was good.

00:43:30.480 --> 00:43:32.880
It was more about awareness.

00:43:34.360 --> 00:43:39.120
Well, the most recent
example is things to do with ads

00:43:39.320 --> 00:43:42.599
and small marketing things
that in the grand scheme

00:43:42.600 --> 00:43:45.839
of things weren't that big
but were implemented

00:43:45.840 --> 00:43:48.119
without considering accessibility,

00:43:48.120 --> 00:43:51.119
mainly because it was meant
to be done really quickly,

00:43:51.120 --> 00:43:55.679
and so probably a whole other list
of things weren't considered.

00:43:55.680 --> 00:43:58.199
We're often trying to also link
accessibility to other key

00:43:58.200 --> 00:44:03.320
areas of online product
development such as security.

00:44:05.800 --> 00:44:06.719
<v Lorna> Privacy.

00:44:06.720 --> 00:44:08.869
Lorenzo: Privacy, exactly.

00:44:08.880 --> 00:44:13.519
Accessibility, for instance, ads,
we're like, "Oh, that shouldn't be there.

00:44:13.520 --> 00:44:14.999
That's clearly not accessible."

00:44:15.000 --> 00:44:18.720
Then we've had to go
back and talk to the team.

00:44:19.240 --> 00:44:22.839
It's rarely done out of malice
or even it's more out of,

00:44:22.840 --> 00:44:25.079
"Oh, this needs to go out quickly,

00:44:25.080 --> 00:44:28.479
we can't consider anything
because we don't have the time."

00:44:28.480 --> 00:44:31.639
Then it's usually spotted by someone
who's involved on that platform,

00:44:31.640 --> 00:44:36.640
and then they'll maybe reach
out to us or spot it themselves.

00:44:37.080 --> 00:44:41.880
I'd say ads are my most recent
experience of this.

00:44:42.680 --> 00:44:48.154
<v Lorna> We haven't really had anybody
do their own accessibility thing,

00:44:50.640 --> 00:44:52.799
or use accessibility.

00:44:52.800 --> 00:44:56.999
We did have a--
I'm not going to name names,

00:44:57.000 --> 00:45:03.599
our developers were using
a functionality that claimed

00:45:03.600 --> 00:45:10.080
to be accessible and has ultimately
proven to be not accessible.

00:45:13.240 --> 00:45:17.159
That was another push
to get our own private

00:45:17.160 --> 00:45:21.400
component library
going that was accessible.

00:45:22.640 --> 00:45:26.560
Our experiences are limited with trying

00:45:26.920 --> 00:45:30.640
to do external
accessibility and bring it in.

00:45:32.920 --> 00:45:34.039
<v Piccia> Great, yes.

00:45:34.040 --> 00:45:37.339
Now, there are a few more questions,
and a couple of them

00:45:37.340 --> 00:45:39.839
you've actually already
answered because one is,

00:45:39.840 --> 00:45:42.279
"I'm curious about the budgeting process.

00:45:42.280 --> 00:45:45.479
What is your experience in dealing
with this investment planning?"

00:45:45.480 --> 00:45:48.559
You've told us how you tell everyone,
"Yes, you can do it later.

00:45:48.560 --> 00:45:50.299
It's going to cost you much more."

00:45:50.300 --> 00:45:51.420
[chuckles]

00:45:51.900 --> 00:45:53.879
Do you want to add anything to that?

00:45:53.880 --> 00:45:58.399
I feel like this question
was put before you handled that.

00:45:58.400 --> 00:46:02.526
I feel already I was like,
"Yes, here's your answer."

00:46:03.380 --> 00:46:04.820
<v Lorna> Yes,

00:46:09.120 --> 00:46:13.679
we definitely work with departments
to budget in accessibility.

00:46:13.680 --> 00:46:16.419
We have matured to that point now

00:46:16.420 --> 00:46:19.919
where they are acknowledging and embracing

00:46:19.920 --> 00:46:24.039
the fact that accessibility
is now something

00:46:24.040 --> 00:46:27.580
they are going to have to invest in,

00:46:27.940 --> 00:46:31.320
literally, with funds and resourcing.

00:46:31.560 --> 00:46:35.130
That was much
more difficult in the beginning.

00:46:35.220 --> 00:46:36.259
[clears throat]

00:46:36.260 --> 00:46:39.659
I don't think if we had gotten that ping

00:46:39.660 --> 00:46:43.880
from our customer in 2013, we would have--

00:46:44.280 --> 00:46:45.759
I don't know where we'd be,

00:46:45.760 --> 00:46:48.759
but there was definitely
a struggle at first

00:46:48.760 --> 00:46:51.599
to get that awareness
and acknowledgment that,

00:46:51.600 --> 00:46:53.399
"Yes, it's going to cost money.

00:46:53.400 --> 00:46:56.045
It's going to be an investment."

00:46:57.780 --> 00:46:59.940
I think then sometimes

00:47:01.400 --> 00:47:04.839
what can be a sell for Sage
as an academic publisher

00:47:04.840 --> 00:47:10.439
who sells to public institutions
who are definitely held accountable

00:47:10.440 --> 00:47:14.280
to have accessible
content is we say, look,

00:47:14.560 --> 00:47:16.999
our customers
are going to be held accountable,

00:47:17.000 --> 00:47:20.119
we're going to lose sales
if we're not accessible.

00:47:20.120 --> 00:47:25.720
Then that money argument becomes
a bit more, "Oh, this is an ROI.

00:47:25.840 --> 00:47:28.360
We do need to invest in this."

00:47:28.680 --> 00:47:31.079
That might be an approach to take

00:47:31.080 --> 00:47:34.719
if you are serving others
and you have a product,

00:47:34.720 --> 00:47:38.159
especially if your customers
demand accessibility,

00:47:38.160 --> 00:47:42.199
then you can put that back and say,
"Look, we need to be accessible.

00:47:42.200 --> 00:47:45.093
We need to literally pay for this."

00:47:47.000 --> 00:47:49.893
<v Piccia> Yes, very, very good point.

00:47:50.440 --> 00:47:55.119
There's another question that says,
"In your experience,

00:47:55.120 --> 00:47:58.699
what do you think
are the most important KPIs

00:47:58.700 --> 00:48:01.979
to present to senior
leadership or executives

00:48:01.980 --> 00:48:03.479
to continue the accessibility work?

00:48:03.480 --> 00:48:08.716
You kind of have already given
us an idea of that with this answer.

00:48:09.480 --> 00:48:11.639
Lorenzo: We once had a question which was,

00:48:11.640 --> 00:48:15.239
how many people are using
this accessibility feature?

00:48:15.240 --> 00:48:18.133
I forget. This was a few years ago.

00:48:19.320 --> 00:48:21.839
We thought, well,
it's not really about the numbers,

00:48:21.840 --> 00:48:25.439
and it's hard to sometimes marry
that accessibility work in terms

00:48:25.440 --> 00:48:29.999
of pure usage because that tends
to be a metric that is often cited.

00:48:30.000 --> 00:48:33.479
Well, how many people
are using the text size widget?

00:48:33.480 --> 00:48:35.216
That was probably it.

00:48:35.560 --> 00:48:41.720
Then we said, "Well, how many people
are using good color contrast?

00:48:41.880 --> 00:48:42.739
Everyone.

00:48:42.740 --> 00:48:44.880
[chuckles]

00:48:45.240 --> 00:48:51.560
When we get asked about pure
quantitative KPIs, we can provide some.

00:48:52.160 --> 00:48:54.359
I think I saw a question about
the UX scorecard.

00:48:54.360 --> 00:48:58.439
That's one way we're trying
to measure that, but often we'll start

00:48:58.440 --> 00:49:02.480
the conversation with not so much
about numbers,

00:49:02.520 --> 00:49:05.456
it's about, one, the user experience.

00:49:05.640 --> 00:49:07.919
It is also about compliance,

00:49:07.920 --> 00:49:10.439
and it's also about
the costs that would incur.

00:49:10.440 --> 00:49:16.019
Those are different risks
and opportunities

00:49:16.020 --> 00:49:18.359
that we're trying to cite
that are not purely,

00:49:18.360 --> 00:49:21.639
"Well, how many people
are going to use this?"

00:49:21.640 --> 00:49:24.759
We found that doesn't translate
well, because it's not really about

00:49:24.760 --> 00:49:28.919
that with a lot of pretty much
all accessibility work,

00:49:28.920 --> 00:49:31.039
but we do get requests to quantify things

00:49:31.040 --> 00:49:34.760
because that's how a lot
of decisions are made.

00:49:35.200 --> 00:49:37.559
That's been a head-scratcher
for a while in terms of,

00:49:37.560 --> 00:49:41.759
well, how do we quantify
this work in a way that's measurable?

00:49:41.760 --> 00:49:43.559
I guess, WCAG compliance is one,

00:49:43.560 --> 00:49:48.319
but we found that that doesn't capture
the entire experience,

00:49:48.320 --> 00:49:51.360
but also the work that goes into it.

00:49:51.640 --> 00:49:56.400
<v Piccia> Yes, so you do use
UX scorecards for accessibility?

00:49:57.040 --> 00:50:03.466
Lorenzo: Yes. That's a fairly recent thing
that the UX team has been implementing.

00:50:03.840 --> 00:50:05.639
When we were talking about it, we said,

00:50:05.640 --> 00:50:08.359
we definitely want
to incorporate accessibility

00:50:08.360 --> 00:50:13.079
as an attribute of a product or
a platform and so the first thing

00:50:13.080 --> 00:50:17.399
was measuring WCAG compliance,
but related to my point before,

00:50:17.400 --> 00:50:22.279
we thought that doesn't really capture
not just the accessibility level,

00:50:22.280 --> 00:50:25.679
but the experience and also
how the team surrounding

00:50:25.680 --> 00:50:28.799
that product is doing,
so we came up with this accessibility

00:50:28.800 --> 00:50:33.719
maturity score and criteria
to measure at what point

00:50:33.720 --> 00:50:35.999
in the accessibility journey
is this team at,

00:50:36.000 --> 00:50:39.570
and is that reflected
in their WCAG compliance

00:50:40.700 --> 00:50:42.979
because that would allow
us to better address

00:50:42.980 --> 00:50:44.919
in which area the team needs to work on,

00:50:44.920 --> 00:50:47.319
whether it's content,
whether it's process,

00:50:47.320 --> 00:50:51.579
whether it's anything else,
